While interesting, this video was frustrating at multiple points because I wanted to engage my brain with the illusions, but it felt as though the speaker continually got in the way of the very thing they were trying to show me.

For All Star, I couldn't hear the words at all until I searched for the piano audio by itself. The video portion wasn't even necessary, but would have enhanced the effect were it not for the constant interruption. My brain takes a moment to synchronize the audio with the expected lyrics, but the speaker's interruptions were so frequent that I was never able to do so in this video. An extended moment of silence, perhaps with the lyrics included at some point, would have really improved this segment.

The segment with the piano giving a speech was the best-presented of all the illusions, but it was still missing a moment where the presenter was silent while a clip played with the captions omitted or obscured, so that the same clip could be re-shown with the captions to reveal the words the piano was "saying". Aside from that minor point, this was the best part of the video.

For the jumping pylon, the speaker was never silent for even one full rotation of the image, so I came away from it feeling like I had no idea if I could hear the illusion. Being silent for five seconds (at least three landings) would have made it clear to me. Similar to the All Star segment, I had to mute the video to confirm that I cannot hear the illusion.

For the Risset Rhythm, the speaker was quiet just long enough for me to recognize the increasing speed, but after hearing the explanation for how it works, I was expecting a segment where the presenter would be quiet long enough for us to hear the transition from rhythm A to rhythm B, accompanied with the animation slowed down to guide us through rhythm A fading out and B fading in. Unfortunately, this didn't happen. As with All Star, I had to look up the rhythm in a separate video.

Illusions, to me, are at their most interesting when one is able to see them both ways and also pick apart our brains as they happen - like that optical illusion where people can see a rabbit or a duck. For audio illusions, hearing them in the first place (or confirming the lack of an illusion) require an extended moment of silence on the part of the presenter, and for the most part, that courtesy was not taken in this video. I do appreciate the information that was presented, but having to find the illusions elsewhere rather than being able to enjoy and examine them in-line took away from the experience.
